[{"title":"Basic MarkDown Grammar","url":"/2020/12/30/Basic%20Markdown/","content":"<h3 id=\"Intro\"><a href=\"#Intro\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Intro\"></a>Intro</h3><p>Since most posts of my blog are wriiten by Markdown, I will take down some basic Markdown grammar. Hope this can help you learn more about Markdown. </p>\n<a id=\"more\"></a>\n<br/>\n\n<h3 id=\"What-is-Markdown\"><a href=\"#What-is-Markdown\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"What is Markdown?\"></a>What is Markdown?</h3><blockquote>\n<p>Markdown is a lightweight markup language for creating formatted text using a plain-text editor. John Gruber and Aaron Swartz created Markdown in 2004 as a markup language that is appealing to the human users in its source form. Markdown is widely used in blogging, instant messaging, online forums, collaboration software, documentation pages, and even readme files.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p align=\"right\">---Wikipedia</p>\n\n<hr>\n<h3 id=\"Grammar\"><a href=\"#Grammar\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Grammar\"></a>Grammar</h3><h4 id=\"Heading\"><a href=\"#Heading\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Heading\"></a>Heading</h4><figure class=\"highlight markdown\"><table><tr><td class=\"code\"><pre><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"section\"># H1</span></span><br><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"section\">## H2</span></span><br><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"section\">### H3</span></span><br><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"section\">#### H4</span></span><br><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"section\">##### H5</span></span><br><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"section\">###### H6</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>\n<h4 id=\"Bold\"><a href=\"#Bold\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Bold\"></a>Bold</h4><figure class=\"highlight markdown\"><table><tr><td class=\"code\"><pre><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"strong\">**bold text**</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>\n<h4 id=\"Italic\"><a href=\"#Italic\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Italic\"></a>Italic</h4><figure class=\"highlight markdown\"><table><tr><td class=\"code\"><pre><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"emphasis\">*italicized text*</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>\n<h4 id=\"Blockquote\"><a href=\"#Blockquote\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Blockquote\"></a>Blockquote</h4><figure class=\"highlight markdown\"><table><tr><td class=\"code\"><pre><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"quote\">&gt; blockquote</span></span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>\n<h4 id=\"Code\"><a href=\"#Code\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Code\"></a>Code</h4><p>``` javascript<br>var canvas = document.getElementById(“canvas”);<br>var context = canvas.getContext(“2d”);<br>```</p>\n<p>i.e. Markdown will render this code with ‘javascript’ grammar.<br>effect:</p>\n<figure class=\"highlight javascript\"><table><tr><td class=\"code\"><pre><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"keyword\">var</span> canvas = <span class=\"built_in\">document</span>.getElementById(<span class=\"string\">&quot;canvas&quot;</span>);</span><br><span class=\"line\"><span class=\"keyword\">var</span> context = canvas.getContext(<span class=\"string\">&quot;2d&quot;</span>); </span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>\n<h4 id=\"Link\"><a href=\"#Link\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Link\"></a>Link</h4><figure class=\"highlight markdown\"><table><tr><td class=\"code\"><pre><span class=\"line\">[<span class=\"string\">title</span>](<span class=\"link\">https://www.example.com</span>)</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>\n<p>effect:<br><a href=\"https://www.darklyh.com/\">Home</a></p>\n<h4 id=\"Horizontal-Line\"><a href=\"#Horizontal-Line\" class=\"headerlink\" title=\"Horizontal Line\"></a>Horizontal Line</h4><figure class=\"highlight markdown\"><table><tr><td class=\"code\"><pre><span class=\"line\">---</span><br></pre></td></tr></table></figure>\n<p>effect:</p>\n\n<hr>\n</br>\nWhat's more, Markdown support HTML5 grammar. This means you can use &ltbr&gt and other grammars in HTML5.\n","categories":["Computer Science"],"tags":["Markdown","Tutorial"]}]